characteristic.英释: very typical of a particular thing or of someone’s character

transportation.英释: a system or method for carrying passengers or goods from one place to another

representative.中释: 代表 a典型的, 有代表性的
representative.英释: someone who has been chosen to speak, vote, or make decisions for someone else

interpretation.英释: the way in which someone explains or understands an event, information, someone’s actions etc

responsibility.英释: a duty to be in charge of someone or something, so that you make decisions and can be blamed if something bad happens

representation.英释: a painting, sign, description etc that shows something

administration.英释: the activities that are involved in managing the work of a company or organization

classification.英释: a process in which you put something into the group or class it belongs to

specialization.英释: an activity or subject that you know a lot about

simplification.英释: You can use simplification to refer to the thing that is produced when you make something simpler or when you reduce it to its basic elements

reconstruction.英释: the work that is done to repair the damage to a city, industry etc, especially after a war

accomplishment.英释: something successful or impressive that is achieved after a lot of effort and hard work

photosynthesis.英释: the production by a green plant of special substances like sugar that it uses as food, caused by the action of sunlight on  chlorophyll (= the green substance in leaves )

correspondence.中释: 通信, 信件, 相符
correspondence.英释: the letters that someone sends and receives, especially official or business letters

infrastructure.中释: 下部构造,基础下部组织
infrastructure.英释: the basic systems and structures that a country or organization needs in order to work properly, for example roads, railways, banks etc

organizational.英释: Organizational abilities and methods relate to the way that work, activities, or events are planned and arranged

administrative.英释: relating to the work of managing a company or organization

generalization.中释: 一般化, 归纳, 概括
generalization.英释: a statement about all the members of a group that may be true in some or many situations but is not true in every case

superintendent.英释: someone who is officially in charge of a place, job, activity etc

hypersensitive.英释: if someone is hypersensitive to a drug, substance etc, their body reacts very badly to it

understandable.英释: understandable behaviour, reactions etc seem normal and reasonable because of the situation you are in

electronically.中释: 电子地, 通过电子手段

systematically.中释: 有系统地, 有条理地

sophistication.英释: The sophistication of people, places, machines, or methods is their quality of being sophisticated

constitutional.英释: officially allowed or limited by the system of rules of a country or organization

supercontinent.英释: a great landmass thought to have existed in the geological past and to have split into smaller landmasses, which drifted and formed the present continents

disappointment.英释: a feeling of unhappiness because something is not as good as you expected, or has not happened in the way you hoped

unsatisfactory.中释: 不令人满意的,不满足的
unsatisfactory.英释: not good enough or not acceptable

recommendation.英释: a suggestion to someone that they should choose a particular thing or person that you think is very good

photogrammetry.英释: the process of making measurements from photographs, used esp in the construction of maps from aerial photographs and also in military intelligence, medical and industrial research, etc

unquestionably.英释: used to emphasize that something is certainly true

counterbalance.英释: Something that is a counterbalance to something else counterbalances that thing

interdependent.英释: depending on or necessary to each other

identification.英释: when someone says officially that they know who someone else is, especially a criminal or a dead person

intellectually.中释: 理智地, 与智力(或思维)有关地

superorganisms.中释: [生]超个体(指群居昆虫等的群体)

counterexample.英释: an example or fact that is inconsistent with a hypothesis and may be used in argument against it

overproduction.英释: the act of producing more of something than people want or need

stratification.英释: when society is divided into separate social classes

overwhelmingly.中释: 压倒性地, 不可抵抗地

conversational.英释: a conversational style, phrase etc is informal and commonly used in conversation

uncontrollably.中释: 无法管束的, 控制不住的

expressionless.英释: an expressionless face or voice does not show what someone thinks or feels

discrimination.英释: the practice of treating one person or group differently from another in an unfair way

pasteurization.中释: 加热杀菌法, 巴斯德杀菌法
pasteurization.英释: the process of heating beverages, such as milk, beer, wine, or cider, or solid foods, such as cheese or crab meat, to destroy harmful or undesirable microorganisms or to limit the rate of fermentation by the application of controlled heat

sensationalism.中释: 追求轰动效应, 感觉论
sensationalism.英释: a way of reporting events or stories that makes them seem as strange, exciting, or shocking as possible – used in order to show disapproval

insurmountable.中释: 不能克服的,不能超越的
insurmountable.英释: an insurmountable difficulty or problem is too large or difficult to deal with

interferometer.英释: any acoustic, optical, or microwave instrument that uses interference patterns or fringes to make accurate measurements of wavelength, wave velocity, distance, etc

philanthropist.英释: a rich person who gives a lot of money to help poor people

unrecognizable.中释: 未被承认的, 无法识别的
unrecognizable.英释: someone or something that is unrecognizable has changed or been damaged so much that you do not recognize them

sentimentalism.中释: 感情主义, 沉于情感
sentimentalism.英释: the state or quality of being sentimental

poikilothermic.英释: (of all animals except birds and mammals) having a body temperature that varies with the temperature of the surroundings

unconventional.中释: 非传统的, 不合惯例的
unconventional.英释: If you describe a person or their attitude or behaviour as unconventional, you mean that they do not behave in the same way as most other people in their society
